In this example, we first load the `tocbibind` package, which allows us to create a TOC that includes both the main sections of the document and the references cited in the bibliography. We also load the `biblatex` package to manage our bibliography and provide a `.bib` file containing some example citations.
The `\maketitle` command generates the document title, author, and date. The `\section` commands define the main sections of the document. Each section is followed by a blank page (using `\newpage`) to provide visual separation between sections.
At the end of the document, we include the bibliography using the `\bibliography` and `\bibliographystyle` commands. The `biblatex` package automatically generates the TOC based on the citations in the bibliography. The resulting TOC will appear at the beginning of the document, providing a quick reference for readers.

To draw a chessboard using LATEX, we can use the `tikz` package along with its `chessboard` library. Here's an example code that uses FEN notation to draw a chessboard:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
    \chessboard[setfen=startfen, color=white, black=teal] { };
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```
In this code, we first load the `tikz` package and its `chessboard` library. Then, we create a `tikzpicture` environment and set the scale to 0.6 (you can adjust this value to make the board larger or smaller). Inside the `tikzpicture` environment, we use the `\chessboard` command with the `setfen` option to specify the initial FEN (Forsyth–Edwards Notation) state of the board. In this example, we've used the string "startfen" for the FEN notation. Replace this with your desired FEN notation.
The `color` and `black` options are used to set the colors of the squares. In this example, we've set the squares to be white with teal (representing black) squares. You can adjust these options to change the colors to your liking.
Save this code in a `.tex` file and compile it with a LaTeX compiler such as TeXstudio or PDFLaTeX to generate a PDF output containing the chessboard drawn according to the provided FEN notation.
Note: To generate an actual playable chessboard, you would need to add additional commands to move pieces around and update the FEN notation accordingly. This example only shows how to draw a static chessboard using FEN notation in LATEX.

